An imposing elderly man came out through the door of the RPG Byty customer centre of the "coal baron" Zdenek Bakal, the largest private owner of apartments for rent in the Czech Republic.
He was carrying under his arm a file with three new rental contracts for three apartments: his own, his daughter and his son who are serving a sentence.
The deregulation increased the rent for these three people.
Instead of paying 3500 the son will have to pay from next year for a 2+1 apartment of second category 4100 crowns.
"And there is no hot water and the heating works with solid fuel," points out on his son's new contract the man who has the signing power.
"But I've signed anyway," he explains angryly and half-resigned.
The citizens' association of BytyOKD.cz apartments, which has described the new rental conditions as "immoral and indecent", advises tenants not to sign and wait until 7 December, when a notice will be published explaining the method to be followed in order to claim.
But man reacts to this with a hand gesture.
"One says that, the other says something else" by frowning the eyebrows.
The Ostrava region becomes the laboratory of deregulation.
After the New Year, this is what awaits most apartments in the Czech Republic whose rents do not correspond to the market price.
For this reason Aktualne.cz decided to personally visit the "laboratory".
The RPG waiting room on Havirovska Street is one of four in the Ostrava region and is already full on Tuesday at 9 a.m.
Right next to the door stands a guard of a security company with a device to call customers.
A special button, "Money 2011", is on the touch screen.
Only one pressure and one paper with a number comes out of the device.
You don't have time to read your number "157" that your number already starts lighting up on the big screen under the top of the waiting room.
In a fraction of a second it's your turn.
After a short while, an old couple arrives to inquire about the rent, but the new rents don't seem to concern people in the waiting room.
The majority of people came to solve common problems like everywhere - demand for repairs, insurance events and so on.
In the Ostrava region, people from more than 44,000 apartments in the RPG portfolio have been receiving mail with new leases in their mailbox since about mid-November.
RPG Byty offers rent increases from 15 to 38 percent.
the special window for new rents has been open to the public since 18 November.
"It's been working for almost a week, so it's still on the test," answers, after a moment of hesitation, the employee behind the counter when the client presents himself as a journalist.
Deragulation and the former miner's apartments in Bakal are a very sensitive local subject.
The vice-president of the parliament and native of the Ostrava Lubomir Zaoralek region of the Social Democrats reported this in a fairly sustained manner before the elections and it now fills the local newspapers.
"20 years after them, I want a new floor."
"They didn't even change me a board put...n in the toilets, soothes in introduction the man mentioned.
However, it is mostly, according to the employees, pensioners who come to make sure that they will receive a discount on the new rent price if they now sign as promised by RPG in a special offer.
This is a rebate of half the amount of rent that will be received by the other loctaries who have signed their new contract before December 15.
But the "deregulation" window on Havirovaska Street is really not overburdened by questions.
