The nursery school is also part of the offices have understood the architects.
the Avriopoint administrative building of Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch. Design.
No one could have expected it to also house a mini kindergarten with everything they need - colored walls, imaginative furniture, toys and finally a miniature playground on the terrace.
Since October last year, the children of Arch. design employees have been able to visit.
The Arch. Design project-architectonic company, whose workshops produced a large number of constructions in Brno, has designed its mini-entrepreneurial school since the first drafts of the Avriopoint building.
It employs about 90 people, especially of age, to make children, and it was important for women architects and project managers to be able to return to work quickly.
At the same time as reduced working time contracts, the nursery school is a bonus offered to its employees by the company Arch. Design. as part of its social program.
Builders and architects have the opportunity to combine work that takes care of children.
It was the employees of Arch.Design themselves who imagined this nursery school and with the support of the management they were able to obtain a grant from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The Mini Kindergarten is financed through the European Social Fund through the Human Resources Operational Programme and the State Budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to the funding (to the tune of 2.8 thousand Czech kronor) they were able to buy equipment and appliances and after two years to provide qualified staff and start up.
After using the funding allocation (two years) the company Arch. Design. has the obligation after 3 years to operate the mini kindergarten on its own funds.
The preparation of the project lasted a year and it was Economy rating that helped to make the staffing request.
Children are cared for by qualified staff, a nurse and a kindergarten teacher attend the children all day long. Children can go to kindergarten without any age limit, but they are more than three years old for the most part.
Since this is a "mini kindergarten" there can only be 5 children present at the same time, but during the day there are more who replace themselves.
The operation of the school is flexible according to the needs of the parents and the children of all employees have the same right to use the school without regard to the hierarchical position.
Although it is an individual care and education, the mini kindergarten programme is comparable to that for pre-school education.
The children do not only play there, but also a quality education is provided - from the beginning to the preparation for school benches English is taught.
The class is equipped not only with imaginative toys and games but also with a computer that children can use.
The presence of small children in society creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can control their child at any time and do not have the stress of being late to pick up children in a school away from the parents' workplace.
Parents therefore use their working time in the most productive way.
It is not surprising that there is a natural relationship of loyalty between the employee and the employer.
Arch.Design.has thus registered as one of the companies that offer a bonus of choice for the recruitment of new employees and are friendly to the family and through this program strengthens HR marketing.
The bone house still fascinates after 100 years. Take a look at the interiors of Gaudi.
The toît resembles the back of a prehistoric saurien, the staircase with a spine of dinosaur and balconies with open fish mouths.
This is the Casa Battlo house in Barcelona by architect Antoni Gaudi.
Because of its organic forms, the house received from the premises the nickname House of Bone.
Organic forms, wild colors, unusual use of stones, fragments of tiles and mosaic, facade reminiscent of scales and everywhere present curves, this is all that is ypic for the Art Nouveau of Antoni Gaudi.
The frontal façade of the house unfolds its dream lines, colors and pleasant textures that remind nature and animals.
During a more detailed observation we see the geometry, rhythm and order thought with precision.
In the night the facade of the house becomes even more dramatic and is lit in such a way that the glossy impression of the colors is reinforced.
The winding and twisting of the shapes also appears in the interiors with the same measure.
The wood copies in waves the window frames, the balustrades, the decorative elements of the doors, the eyelet and the slats.
The Battlo house that stands in the Eixample district in the Passeig de Gracia shopping street at the number 43, was born from the construction of a house of 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortes.
The reconstruction took place for two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, Joseph Battlo, a wealthy entrepreneur, first insisted on the demolition of the old construction and the construction of another brand new but quickly accepted Gaudi's idea of an unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
But the idea of Casa Battlo as a multi-unit house was not thought of by Gaudi alone.
Architect Josep Maria Jujol worked with him.
It is precisely on his project that the decorations for an apartment of representation of the owner of the building and the use of the mosaic for the facade were born.
For the facade have also worked other artists and creators.
Joint work for Casa Battlo's plans began with successful cooperation between Jujol and Gaudi.
Jujol took part in the construction of Gaudi Casa Mila's house and the Guell Park, in which there are other works by Gaudi.
The premises nicknamed the house hot just after it was finished because of its organic forms "the House of Bone".
Others, having regard to the specific mechanism of opening windows, called it "the house that shoves".
It is said that at the top of the building there is a sword similar to that of Saint George the patron saint of Catalonia.
Other sculpture elements of the construction contain hidden religious motifs.
Gaudi has designed for the house a unique system in its central heating time, with vents and typical chimneys.
Their inclination of 45 degrees seems strange.
During the creation Gaudi did not comply with the construction guidelines of the time and did not allow themselves to be obstructed by them.
At the beginning of the construction he obtained from the city the building permit, knowing, of course, that the data on the reconstruction plans were so vague that two years later during the finish the city council was horrified and asked for modifications.
For example, the members of the municipal council did not like the building pillars to encroach on the public sidewalk.
There was never any change, but on the contrary, only 15 days after the call of the city Josep Battlo asked (and obtained satisfaction) for permission to rent the two highest floors.
The owner moved to the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a common living room and on the third a bedroom and a private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewellery store.
The entire six-story house is shared by a staircase through which you can access to a separate roof terrace.
All right angles and straight lines were cancelled by the basic elements of the reconstruction and their replacement by curved walls.
Gaudi also worked on the modern concept of space liaison.
The common part can be connected completely by opening the doors of the salons and the high society can communicate comfortably or limit itself the private space for more intimate interviews.
The house with the reconstruction of Gaudi has received in addition to new facades a non-traditional roof and two additional floors.
Gaudi's play with light is also impressive, blue and white glazed tiles with which is decorated the inner courtyard and with lights wells.
The two-color game gives maximum light in all floors of the house.
It was simply enough to bet on the principle that white reflects more than the dark one, which on the contrary absorbs the rays of the sun.
Casa Battlo, which was registered in 2005 in the UNESCO World Heritage Fund, can be visited by everyone.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and splendid apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to take this step in 2002 on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
They continued the visits because they found that it was a lucrative business and they expanded the field of visits to common areas and attic including the roof terraces.
The entrance ticket to the monument is really cheap and costs 16.50 euros; students, pensioners, groups and tourist cardholders have 20 percent discount.
The sum is still above the entry price in Gaudi's other constructions in the city.
If you want to feel the real atmosphere of the house with its fantastic turrets, you must quickly find a comrade among the inhabitants of the building and visit the house completely.
