Devices to track people are increasingly being requested by parents who want to monitor their children.
Fear for their child leads more and more people to think of monitoring them through a GPS.
The system, set up at the beginning to search for cars can just as well be used to trace the movement of people and help for some cases as by exmple that of the little Anicka Janatkova.
The instrument is currently as big as a match box but will soon be the size of a watch.
The case of Little Anicka has moved a large number of people and they have begun to look for ways to better protect their children.
Even if the price is to disturb their privacy.
"We are trying to tell everyone that this is not espionage but only another way to reduce the likelihood that there will be another tragedy," says Petr Pilin of the company MAcro Weil, which is one of the suppliers of tracing devices on the Czech market.
"I confess that there may be cases of misuse of such devices, such as putting it in the bag of a person who is not aware of it, but I have not yet encountered such cases."
"The majority of people are customers who actually buy the product for security reasons," said Pilin.
According to him, children should always know for what purposes "the box" is used and how to use it in an emergency.
The child psychologist, Dana Bockova, draws attention that if the child does not want to carry something of this type on him, he will get rid of it.
'And even the smaller ones can show great creativity when it comes to getting rid of something on purpose when they don't want to be under control'.
"Mobile phones, which can be cut off like these tracking devices, have already led parents to long expectations," says Bockova.
According to her, the fact that this type of device can help in the event of an attack is highly questionable.
"If it is a prepared rapt, the author will do everything to ensure that the child does not have an electronic device that can locate him".
"Currently, it's the phone."
"As soon as tracing devices develop, they (criminals) will also look for them because the sale will be supported by an advertising campaign".
"In such cases criminals will always be ahead of the police," says the psychologist.
She admits that such devices can help in an unprepared assault by a paedophile.
According to Robert Cech of RC Monitoring, who offers tracking services for both cars and people, says having this type of device can help, even if it is destroyed in the event of an attack.
"The apparatus may be configured in such a way that it is on a regular basis after a specified period of time".
"In the event that the device is destroyed, the last position of the person concerned remains."
"The more expensive devices also have an incline meter that immediately signals the position of the person who has slipped and is in an elongated position without moving," says Cech.
According to him so-called smart mobile phones that are equipped with a navigation system, can offer a comparable service after formatting it with a special prologiciel.
The problem with the current tracking systems is that it is either a device similar to those worn as a pendant the size of a match box or smaller telephone devices.
We can always lose them.
According to Pilina of the company Macro Weil, that is why tests are being conducted to make devices that look like common digital watches.
"This will have the advantage that the potential attacker will not be able to recognize the tracking device."
"Or he will realize after a while, which will have given the police a little more time," he adds.
Whether the tracking device is developed in the form of a bracelet or pendant, it will always use the same technology as to trace cars.
This is a combination of GPS-based position acquisition systems (which is commonly used in autonavigation) and a mobile phone function that alerts the current position of a vehicle.
