A longer index than the ring finger is a sign of low risk of cancer
Men with a longer index than the ring finger are at a lower risk of prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published on Wednesday by the British magazine Cancer.
This may depend on the level of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our findings show that the relative length of the finger serves as a simple test of prostate cancer risk, especially for men before the age of 60," declared the co-author of the Ros Eeles study, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help determine which men should be tested for prostate cancer, in particular by combining with genetic risk or other aggravating factors such as family health antecedents, added Eeles.
During the period 1994-2009 she followed with her colleagues in Britain more than 1500 patients with prostate cancer and at the same time nearly three thousand healthy men.
More than half of the participants in the study had the right hand index shorter than the ring finger.
For them as for the 19 percent of those with the same length of fingers, the same probability of prostate cancer was found.
For those who had the index longer than the ring finger, however, the risk fell to 33 per cent, for men before 60 years of age the risk decreased to 87 per cent.
The length ratio of the two mentioned fingers - formed during the prenatal period - indicates inter alia different levels of sexual hormones to which the child is exposed in the uterus.
Unless testosterone matches a longer index.
Previous research had shown that it is precisely testosterone that helps develop prostate cancer.
Professor Vacla Paces, a renowned Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, said for TKC that he is aware of this study but that it does not seem to him that the relationship between finger length and cancer is "completely demonstrated".
