The Japanese Fujitsu group relocates its branch from Bad Homburg to Frankfurt.
As stated on Wednesday by the giant specialized in the manufacture and maintenance of computers, next year in July, the workplace of 400 men and women, located so far in Marienbader Square of the city of Bad Homburg, will be transferred to Astro Park, an immense office complex located on Lyoner Straße Street in the Niederrad district of Frankfurt.
A Fujitsu spokesperson explained that in the medium term, the group is expected to have 100 more jobs scattered so far in the region.
The rental offer has been extremely attractive. Furthermore, the open-plan offices of Astro Park are better suited to the way employees work.
Also in Bad Homburg, Fujitsu was just a tenant.
Managing Director Bernd Wagner said: "Frankfurt-Niederrad is for us a prime location with remarkable infrastructure".
He claims that the connection to the airport is very important for a global company like Fujitsu.
The new move of a major company within the region yesterday brought joy to the winners and caused disappointment to the losers.
The head of economic affairs of the municipality of Frankfurt, Mr. Markus Frank (CDU), said that once again, a "global actor" had been conquered.
It is a "extraordinary profession of faith relative to the place of implantation".
Fujitsu is suitable for the city and its location is an important boost for Niederrad.
The mayor of Bad Homburg, Michael Korwisi (the Greens), regrets Fujitsu's decision.
