"I have the hope that the owner and landlord of the building will be cooperative."
Ten years ago, the building of the Place de l'Hôtel de Ville, used so far by Fujitsu and the nearby "small vertical", as well as the rest of the buildings of Marienbad Square, were part of the controversial construction project of the spa.
The result of a joint project by the municipality and a private project developer, a new entrance to the city was created between the railway station and the Town Hall, which aroused many criticisms, not only because of the impressive layout of the surfaces that used to be used in part as parking, but also because of the height of the buildings.
In 2001, the investment rating and consulting company, Feri, the computer manufacturer for travel distribution systems, Start Amadeus, and Fujitsu, a computer manufacturer at the time still associated with Siemens, moved into the buildings.
In 2006, the German group in Frankfurt specialising in Immobilien-Chancen bought the buildings occupied by Fujitsu at the same time as the Morgan Stanley real estate fund. A year later, these buildings were sold to the Spanish company Falcon Real Estate Investments SA based in Madrid.
The Fujitsu Group headquartered in Tokyo considers itself the third largest supplier of IT products in the world.
