Four girls who had barely spent their teens in white gloves, dressed in identical olive-coloured jackets and trousers, were freezing at your attention.
Four pairs of black heeled shoes, aligned to the rule.
Four neat hats perfectly perched at the top of hair attached by a striped knot in blue and white.
"Personally, I think they have an average appearance," said Mr. Tang, disdainfully.
"The models are pretty."
More than one government has tried to refresh the image of China's urban inspectors.
One city demanded that all new recruits have a graduate degree.
Guangdong Province exchanged the grey-green uniforms for a so-called more engaging blue.
Wuhan, in Central China, replaced the lower eyes with the strong way: in 2009, a report reported that 50 officers had surrounded an uncontrollable snack cart by throwing black eyes, firmly for half an hour, until the colporteur packs his things and leaves.
Xindu, an urban district of 680,000 inhabitants in Chengdu, chose to do a large image operation.
Since 2003, the district has completed its street police in urban areas with 13 women, specially chosen for their appearance, galbe and young age.
The idea is to give the rough police a softer, more feminine side.
Unfortunately, even Scarlett Johansson could have difficulty attracting attention to this underground urban brigade of China.
And for good reason, the critics will say.
Unlike the police, these officers are only allowed to enforce municipal ordinances by imposing fines or other administrative sanctions.
But the Chinese media portray news of a different reality.
In January 2008, the Hubei provincial inspectors beat an observer to death after he used his mobile phone to film them dispersing a protest against a waste dump.
Last year, a training manual for Beijing inspectors, stolen and posted, describes how to effectively defeat offenders without emitting blood.
This year in Shanghai, a watermelon peddler was abandoned with a brain injury after a fight with five officers.
A video game imbued with violence, available by online download, shows Chinese inspectors trained in assaulting street vendors.
