Prosecutors will not charge Senator Ensign
The prosecutors of the Department of Justice lifted the criminal charges against Senator John Ensign, arising from a case involving an assistant in a former campaign and his efforts to obtain lobbying work for the wife's husband, announced on Wednesday the senator's lawyers.
The decision put an end to the most serious legal threat faced by Mr Ensign, the Nevada Republican who was considered a possible Republican candidate for the 2012 presidential election until the scandal surrounding his case did not make the national headlines last year and harmed his career.
Mr Ensign's office stated that he was "very happy" with the decision, which was the result of a one-year investigation.
The honourable senator could still be exposed to disciplinary measures taken by the Senate Ethics Committee.
Mr. Ensign's counsel stated that the Department of Justice had "informed that Senator Ensign was no longer the subject of the investigation and that he did not intend to maintain any charges against him in this case."
The Department of Justice refrained from commenting on this matter.
The announcement came as a kind of surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Department of Justice, according to which there would be significant evidence that Mr. Ensign was conspired to violate a federal criminal prohibition on lobbying.
Interviews, e-mails and other documents, first released in October 2009 in the New York Times, indicated that Mr.Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, one of his assistants, obtain lucrative lobbying work to win the silence of Mr.Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, about the senator's case with her.
Ms. Hampton once served as treasurer in an Ensign campaign.
Mr. Ensign contacted a number of political funders to find work for Mr. Hampton and then defended their rights after they hired Mr. Hampton to lobby for them; in accordance with documents and interviews.
Since Mr. Hampton had recently been a collaborator of Mr. Ensign, he was prohibited for a year by law from lobbying his former employer or the Senate as a whole.
Ethics experts argued that the unusual agreement between Mr. Ensign and Mr. Hampton, who were close friends before the case, appears to be in contradiction with the so-called ban on the rotating door of lobbying.
According to the evidence that has been made public, "there seems to be prima facie evidence of a conspiracy to violate and of a substantial violation of the law of the revolving door," said Stanley Brand, a Washington lawyer who specializes in the defence of clients of a government investigation.
Although the department's judge refused to explain the reasoning that led to the decision in Ensign, Mr. Brand and other ethics lawyers said that the department appeared to be wary of political prosecution after a number of high-level setbacks from its Public Integrity section, including last year's decision to drop the prosecution of former Senator Ted Stevens on charges of misconduct.
Federal prosecutors are clearly afraid to take up arms," said Melanie Sloan, the Director General of Citizens for Accountability and Ethics in Washington, a defence group that received several complaints against Mr. Ensign in the case.
"This basicly says high-ranking government official can now assume the laws don't apply to them", she added.
Paul Coggins, Senior Counsel for Mr. Ensign, stated in an interview that on Monday he had received a telephone call from a Department of Justice prosecutor and a follow-up the following day, telling him that the department was not looking for charges against his client.
Mr. Ensign's team of lawyers had cooperated with the prosecutors in an attempt to persuade them that the senator, as his office reaffirmed in a statement on Wednesday, "had acted in accordance with the law."
Mr. Coggins refused to clarify the legal arguments he had made to the prosecutor's office.
"I'm not comfortable going into the details of my discussions with the Department of Justice, except to say that we think they made the right decision," he said.
Last month, the Federal Election Commission decided to abandon an investigation following an independent complaint by the ethics group, claiming that the payment of $96,000 by Mr. Ensign's parents to the Hamptons violated the federal election law.
The election commission stated that it did not have enough evidence to prove that the money was anything but a gift.
NV Energy, a major Nevada company that has long supported the senator, is a company for which Mr.Ensign has helped Mr.Hampton find lobbying work.
An e-mail sent in December 2008 showed that, after the company welcomed Mr. Hampton as a lobbyist, Mr. Ensign's Chief of Staff, John Lopez, contacted Mr. Hampton and told him that he was "marting" the Department of the Interior on a contentious issue.
Mr. Ensign also attended a luncheon with Mr. Hampton and another Nevada client, Allegiant Air, and asked the Secretary of Transportation to schedule a meeting on behalf of the airline after hiring Mr. Hampton to lobby.
When the news of the case surfaced last year, Mr. Ensign apologized to his constituents and resigned from his position as leader in the fourth Republican rank in the Senate.
After keeping a low profile for several months, Mr.Ensign stated two weeks ago that he intended to run for a third term in the Senate.
In announcing that Mr.Ensign was no longer the target of a criminal investigation, his spokesperson, Jennifer Cooper, stated that the honourable senator hoped that the ethics committee would quickly follow the example of the Department of Justice and end its investigation.
Senator Ensign is pleased to continue his hard work on behalf of the people of Nevada, she says.
