Every minute they sent reports of horrific testimonies via Twitter.
In the end, the defense said that there were more than 140,000 messages about the rape trial and the children attached to their beds in a house that was burned down.
On Thursday, the widely followed trial of Steven J. Hayes, who was found guilty of the murder of three members of the Cheshire family in Connecticut, should lead to an official end where the judge would impose the death penalty, voted by the jury.
But Mr. Hayes' lawyers have already filed evidence in the court that outlines appeal arguments, which could occupy the courts for years.
What is provocative is that the intense reporting on the trial - as well as the widespread and widespread use by Twitter journalists - created a "circus atmosphere", a saturation so widespread and instant with incendiary details that the jury was badly influenced by the public's passions.
The application could lead appeal judges to debate whether new technologies require new rules in courtrooms.
