The defence lawyers claim that they will also challenge the constitutionality of the death penalty and that they will argue that the judge unfairly expelled one of the jurors, who had been critical before the prosecutors, and that he improperly put pressure on a verdict by making the unusual decision to have the jury deliberate over a weekend.
The jurors have not been kidnapped.
But their arguments on the effect of the intense media coverage of the trial could be the greatest source of interest.
They noted in a protest against the verdict, tabled last month, that the case dominated the media scene in Connecticut and that it was discussed during the election campaign by candidates for the post of Governor and the United States Senate.
They maintained that the computer media kept on fuelling the flames of the emotion of the affair.
