Can civility bring cleavages together?
After a campaign marked by invective and negativity, a minimum of civility broke out in Washington this week.
Is it a forerunner of true bipartite cooperation forward or an illusory moment before the rapid return to partisan struggle in the capital?
The Tuesday meeting between President Obama and Congressional leaders did not produce any breakthroughs on the major issues that must be addressed during the session of the "dirty duck".
But obviously, there was at least a polite discussion about the differences between the two sides as well as the recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than another episode where each side wanted to score points.
The public meeting on Wednesday of the committee on the president's deficit was equally civilized, despite the political differences that remain between the members.
It seems clear that the close interaction of several months has created mutual respect transcending the ideological gap; but which, however, still divides the members.
It's barely enough to say that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
Both sides are now in a period of trial and mutual testing in order to obtain signs of cooperation and compromise, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and voter patience for a renewed partisan war.
That is why the Tuesday meeting and subsequent comments from participants revealed a minimum of requirements or charges.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too large and too deep to suggest a rapid change in the climate that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it is taxation, spending, health care or rights, both parties remain miles away.
However, the November election had moderated Washington, at least in the short term.
"There is no doubt that things have changed in the tone," said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official, now alongside the Centre for Ethics and Public Policy.
"It's inevitable after the elections.
The elections arouse partisan passions and then fade.
That's good."
On some issues, such as those on the agenda of the "dirty duck" session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush's tax cuts will expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favour of that.
Both parties want to find a way to preserve some or all of them, either permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, a compromise is possible on the extension of unemployment benefits, if only because Republicans cannot afford to give the impression that they are in favour of tax cuts for the rich, while refusing unemployment benefits to unemployed workers.
After Tuesday's meeting in the White House, there was more optimism about a possible agreement on the issues raised during the session on the lame duck, with the ratification of the New START Pact.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warned that fruitful cooperation on the most pressing issues of the "lame duck" session would not necessarily lead to a better understanding between the two parties when the 112th congress met in January.
Instead, he said, a period of disagreement is likely, if not inevitable.
"Once the things that must be done are done, psychology in the short term will return to one of the confrontations," he said.
Wehner also expressed his widely shared scepticism that civility would lead to genuine cooperation.
"I consider most of what is going on between today and 2012 as a pre-spectacle or a shadow-boxing compared to the main event of 2012, he said.
The reasons are closely related to the composition of the new Republican majority in the House and to the voters present in the tea which contributed to its creation.
However, Republican leaders are aware of the dangers if they go too far, they know that they must try to live up to their promises to reduce public spending and repeal the new Health Care Act.
These partisan positions are already clear in the first reactions to the recommendations of the Deficit Committee which include reforming the tax code and increasing certain taxes, extending the retirement age and reducing spending.
Co-Chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles chose one of the most difficult tasks in Washington and, in their view, imposed the deficit on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes on the 18-member commission to issue their plan as a formal recommendation, and they have had difficulty reaching that number.
The greatest resistance remains among the group's elected representatives, suggesting that there are few reasons or willingness to compromise on tax issues, at least today.
Galston foresees two phases in the fighting between the White House and the Republicans of Congress.
The first will come next year in the form of partisan confrontations, as Republicans challenge Obama in terms of budget, taxes and health care, and then be followed by a period of greater bipartite cooperation.
What would be the cause of change?
Public opinion.
There is ample evidence that, despite the partisan spirit of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see both parties work together.
If the confrontation leads to an impasse, as in 1995, then both parties will carefully observe the reaction of the public.
The person who will be judged in loss will have to change course and find compromises.
But that would be an optimistic point of view.
The partisan spirit and polarization are greater today than they were in the mid-1990s, and there seems to be a greater ideological gap between Obama and the Republicans of Congress than there was then between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as a simple prelude to a more consistent election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civility exposed this week could be appreciated by many Americans.
But it will take much more effort on the part of both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
