Khmer Rouge veterans forced to face the past
In a poorly lit classroom with poor quality decrepit concrete walls, the director of Anlong Veng High School spoke of the man who built it, the last Khmer Rouge leader, Ta Mok.
"Everyone here loves Ta Mok."
"He was a good leader, and he cared about his people," said 42-year-old Sreng Kor Ma.
Known as "the butcher" for his brutality, when he was at the helm of the Khmer Rouge, this commander remains popular in this isolated bastion of former Khmer Rouge in north-western Cambodia where he had hospitals, bridges and other infrastructure built; and where thousands of former soldiers of the organization still live today.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge surrendered to the government, long-standing loyalty is finally called into question in Anlong Veng.
In April, a local forum for truth and reconciliation allowed victims to face publicly the people who had participated in the regime.
In June, the government distributed a high school textbook that, for the first time, taught Khmer Rouge history to the children of its former soldiers.
And in July, a Cambodian court, jointly led by the United Nations, handed down its first sentence against a former member of the Khmer Rouge, sentencing, to 35 years in prison, the former head of the infamous Tuol Sleng torture centre, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as "Duch".
In view of this development, anxiety has increased among the Khmer Rouge veterans of Anlong Veng, complicating reconciliation efforts and their willingness to reintegrate into Cambodian society.
"There is resentment and fear among the former Khmer Rouge but they are powerless to do anything," said Chhang Youk, director of the Cambodia Documentation Centre, an independent body that conducts research on the regime.
"For them, life under the Khmer Rouge was glorious but the regime became a symbol of evil."
"The situation generates divisions within families."
During the Khmer Rouge rule in Cambodia, between 1975 and 1979, about 1.7 million people were executed or died of hunger, disease or overwork.
When the Vietnamese invaded and overthrowd Pol Pot's government in 1979, the rest of the regime and its army fled to Cambodia's border with Thailand.
There, they launched an insurrection that lasted until the last of the movements came in December 1998.
While Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary were leading the guerrillas at their base in the mountains of western Cambodia and in the jungle, Ta Mok was preparing a suite at Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, after a UN-sponsored peace agreement led to the country's first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Khmer Rouge fighters began defection to the government, culminating in the surrenders of Ieng Sary in 1996 and Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998 and Ta Mok, who had held the lead, was captured by government forces in 1999 in the mountains near Dangrek.
He died in a Phnom Penh prison in 2006 pending trial.
Without their benefactors, most Khmer Rouge veterans have fallen into black poverty, common to the rural areas of Cambodia; and many remain nostalgic of the movement.
Although a few Khmer Rouge elite officers kept their local leadership positions in exchange for laying down their arms, they are unskilled farmers of low rank and file.
"These people received very little follow-up after the surrender," said Sok Leang of the Centre for Justice and Reconciliation, which organizes public forums throughout Cambodia, including in Anlong Veng.
"They are soaked in the agrarian utopian ideology of the regime."
"They were raised in a setting where doing business is a foreign concept."
Sor Lim, 55 years old, who joined the Khmer Rouge as a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle around Anlong Veng before settling in 1998 as a poor rice farmer.
"Life under the Khmer Rouge was good," he said.
"Your Mok feeds everyone."
But now life is difficult because we have to support ourselves."
The ongoing Khmer Rouge Court has also caused concern here.
The court should, at the beginning of next year, begin the judgement of Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, Ieng Thirith, another former Khmer red minister.
The court's mandate is to try the senior leaders and principals responsible for the crimes, but he did not say whether he was pursuing more than those four cases.
It would take more to calm the fears in Anlong Veng.
The latest media speculations turned to 64-year-old Im Chaem, a former district chief in Banteay Meanchey province under the Khmer Rouge in the 1970s.
In 2007, she told the researchers at the Cambodia Documentation Centre that she had supervised the construction of the Trapeang Thma Dam, a project where thousands of forced workers were reportedly killed.
Recently, during a torrid evening, Im Chaem returned from work to the field near his wooden house on stilts, on a dirt road outside Anlong Veng.
As the sun cast long shadows on dry grass, Im Chaem refused to discuss his past within the Khmer Rouge.
If the court summoned her, she said, she would refuse to go.
"Cambodia is at peace and stable," she said.
"If there's more prosecution, there'll be war."
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who defected from the Khmer Rouge in 1978, has also repeatedly warned that instability would occur if the court prosecuted several suspects, although experts and historians dispute this.
"Cambodia needs to dig a hole and bury the past," he said.
But facing the past is all Cambodia needs to do to move forward, says Youk Chhang, from the documentation centre.
"Reconciliation in Khmer terms is to reconnect broken pieces," he says.
"We have to put these pieces together so we can understand."
The centre produced the first government-approved manual on Khmer Rouge, "A History of Democratic Kampuchea, made up of 75 pages."
He distributed it to Anlong Veng in June as a supplement to the Ministry of Education's history manuals, designed for high schools, which contained less than four pages on the Khmer Rouge.
As in most Cambodia, Anlong Veng's youth know only a few details about the Khmer Rouge, despite the city's links to the regime.
Touch Valeak, 19, a student at Anlong Veng's high school, said the new manual helped students understand an important part of their history.
But his parents reacted with skepticism when he came home with the book to study.
"My family rejects many parts of the manual and the court," he says.
"They don't trust each other because they don't know exactly how many people the court will pursue."
Such resistance has made the reconciliation process complex and difficult, said Sok Leang.
But the public forums, the manual and the court are starting to have an impact, he said.
Yet, the Khmer Rouge retain a powerful attraction here.
In the heights of the mountains of Dangrek, a path, invaded by weeds and dotted with plastic bags, leads to a black soot rectangle, covered with a rusty sheet roof.
Pol Pot's body was burned here on a pile of tires after his death in 1998.
Nuom Sothea, 31, a roadside mobile phone dealer, said she didn't know much about the man who was cremated there.
"But he has a great spirit; and many people go there to pray," she said.
