Sport and fraud of the law
The tricks similar to Alonso's and Ramos's against Ajax demonstrate ingenuity but not the desire to escape punishment.
In principle, the expulsion of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) during the November 23 match against Ajax in the Champions League caused a lot of ink on the anti-sportive character of such behaviour and whether the two players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As we know, a few minutes before finishing the game (which their team already won clearly), the two players deliberately lost time when they made mistakes to determine the referee to show them the second yellow card.
Thus, and given that Real Madrid will eventually be the leader of his group, the two players will complete the regulatory sanction during the next match of the dam match against Auxerre and will be able to pass without cards in the next phase.
Finally, UEFA's discipline committee sanctioned team coach José Mourinho with two games and various economic sums to the players involved.
The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances like this or similar is not a new practice, if not rather frequent in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, unwritten rules, but followed, of this sport.
Part of the debate that appeared in the related case is due to the fact that this had as protagonist a team of the entity of Real Madrid (which in its anthem displays nobility and honour and which on past occasions condemned to a fine to its players for similar acts) and to the dramatization orchestrated, it seems, by Mourinho, which adds one more episode to his dilated story of histrionic technician and provocative.
In any case, the debate asks whether this type of behaviour does not expressly prohibit by the regulation contradict the principles of sport, i.e. whether these actions commit a fraud of law; for they are indeed actions that respect the sports regulation, but seem to avoid its meaning.
The question is to examine the type of harm they cause to the sports spirit.
One of the assets that includes the sports spirit is the physical integrity of the opposing players, an aspect that with these actions was not endangered, that is, there was no violent game.
Another of these assets that is alluded to with the correct game is to prevent the team of infractors from benefiting unfairly from the opposite team, which is also not the case.
However, the paradoxical fact of the action of the Real Madrid players is that it does not accommodate what is normally characterized as cheating or fraud of the law, because its violation of the rules was not carried out in hiding to try to avoid the sanction, but their action precisely tried to be as obvious as possible to receive the penalization of the arbitrator.
They were waiting and willingly accepted the sanction.
Another issue is the type of advantage that infractors obtain from the intended errors examined.
Here it seems necessary to note that one does not put in a situation of disadvantage to the rival and one does not get an advantage in the same match either, because obviously the result of the action presupposes the fact of leaving their own team with fewer players.
And it's not a useful strategy for the next game either, because the club wouldn't be able to count on these players.
Obviously the advantage is that the players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that can threaten their participation in a future game.
But this is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indetermination, as the team could be eliminated suddenly and apart from that, with this action the players complete a sanction match and move on to the second cycle of cards, in which the suspension due to the accumulation of cards occurs with one less than in the first cycle.
So, climbing the ladder, it's not so clear that it's an advantage.
Ultimately, these actions are not contrary to the spirit of sport, which nevertheless forms part of strategic decisions that promote the maximum benefit of what the rules allow.
In our case, the players did not act to avoid the application of the sanction (it would indeed be a clear case of fraud of the law),m otherwise they chose instead the moment in which they submitted to it.
They made a strategic decision without defeating the penalty or escaping that one.
Even though the border between genius and fraud of the law is diffuse, on this occasion I think we had a clear case of genius.
The controversy, it seems to me, appears because of two factors: because there were two self-expulsions and because of the way in which the director was passed on to provoke them.
The harm caused to the principles of sport by these actions is not as ethical as aesthetic.
