The European Union changes the rules for obtaining a visa
Individuals must go to the Visa Applicant Service Centres prior to their interview in the Consular Section; the cost of waiting time will be reduced.
As of January 10, 2011, the visa processing procedure at the United States Embassy and Consulates will change.
Under the new procedure, the majority of applicants will have to report to the Visa Applicant Service Centres (CSA, as its acronyms in English) prior to their interview in the Consular Section.
CSA staff will take the applicant's biometric information, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages for aspiring candidates, including the following:
The total cost to process the visa will be lower, it will no longer be necessary to make a payment to get an appointment, another payment for the processing of the visa and another for the mail service to deliver the document.
The aspirant will make a one-time payment that will cover all three services.
The current tariff will remain the same: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visa applications (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for business and investor visas.
Those wishing to renew their visa will not be required to attend an interview with the Consular Representative, they will only report to the nearest CSA where they will present the documents and take their fingerprints.
Because biometric information will be captured in the CSA, applicants who wish a second appointment to be interviewed in the Consular Section will remain in the CSA for less time than before.
Similarly, visa applicants at the Consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra service fee of $26.
For further information on the new visa application procedure, visit http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
