A Global Plan to Renovate Lighting
Yesterday, the UN proposed in Cancún a plan to renovate domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries with a view to achieving a reduction in greenhouse gases (GHGs), which corresponds to almost one third of the additional reduction needed to stabilize the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is in line with the major concrete projects that the United Nations hopes to adopt in Cancún to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments by industrialized countries.
According to the plan tabled yesterday, if the incandescent bulbs that still monopolize between 50 and 70% of the market were replaced by compact fluorescent bulbs or, better, by light-emitting diode bulbs (LED or LED) in English, most of the 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of GHG emitted on the planet to enlighten humans would be avoided.
Lighting accounts for 8% of global emissions.
This is the equivalent of 70% of emissions from the global fleet.
In Copenhagen last year, major emitters, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans that are expected to increase aggregate GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But this balance sheet will have to be subtracted from 5 Gt in order to stabilize by 2020 the climate increase to 2 degrees centigrade in order to prevent it from becoming out of control.
In incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy dissipates as heat and the rest, 5%, produces light.
With compact fluorescent bulbs, the energy expenditure is reduced by 75% and with the new LED bulbs, this energy requirement is reduced by twice again.
Fluocompact bulbs last an average of 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
New LED bulbs, such as those launched by manufacturer Philips this week - this company participated in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, giving an idea of the possible economy with a replacement plan that would apply to 100 countries.
These all-new bulbs can also work with rheostats in addition to generating very little heat.
And they contain no mercury.
Several specialists have shown reservations about compact fluorescent light bulbs as they contain mercury and need to be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries unless manufacturers put in place instructions.
But, according to the report, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the fluocompact light bulb, but rather coal-fired power plants, which emit a lot of mercury to produce electricity wasted in incandescent light bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tonnes of mercury per year.
The report details the gains each country would make through this international programme.
For example, Indonesia would save $1 billion per year in electricity purchases and eight million tonnes of CO2, equivalent to 3.5 thermal power plants, which would cost Indonesia 2.5 billion.
