Hackers avengers and spies in diligence
The WikiLeaks case has double value.
On the one hand, it turns out to be an apparent scandal, a scandal that appears as a scandal only before the hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes at the international level, and foreshadows a future dominated by regression.
But let's proceed by order.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation that every file made up of a secret service (of any nation) consists exclusively of press clippings.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual habits only bring back what for months could be read in any newspaper (except those of which Berlusconi owns), and Khadafi's sinisterly caricatural profile was long ago for the artists of cabaret matter to sketch.
The rule that secret records should be composed of only news already known is essential to the dynamics of secret services, and not only in this century.
If you go to a bookshop dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each book repeats (on the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rose-Croix) exactly what was already written in earlier books.
And this is not only because the author of occult texts does not like to do unpublished research (and does not know where to look for news about the non-existent), but because those who dedicate themselves to occultism believe only in what they already know, and who reconfirms what they have already learned.
It's the mechanism of Dan Brown's success.
Same for the secret files.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or with a limited mind) the head of the secret services (if not he could be, what do I know, editor at Libération), who holds only what he recognizes as true.
The top secret information about Berlusconi that the American embassy in Rome sent to the State Department was the same as that which Newsweek published the week before.
So why did the revelations on these files make so much noise?
On the one hand, they say what every educated person already knows, namely that the embassies, at least since the end of the Second World War, and since the heads of state could call themselves or take a plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of a few small representation exercises, have turned into espionage centers.
Any spectator of investigative films knows this very well, and it is only by hypocrisy that one pretends to ignore it.
However, public repetition violates the duty of hypocrisy, and serves to place American diplomacy in a bad light.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker can capture the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world is a significant blow to the prestige of the State Department.
Therefore, the scandal does not put victims so much in crisis as the "bursts".
But come to the deep nature of what happened.
Once, in Orwell's day, we could conceive of all power as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
The Orwellian prophecy had proved completely since, being able to control every movement through the telephone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the highway used and so on, the citizen became the total victim of the eye of power.
But when we show, as it happens now, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control report ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker - elected as the avenger of the citizen - can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that no longer has the ability to keep its own secrets hold?
It is true, as Georg Simmel already said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that all knowledge of the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is indeed an empty secret, because it is within the public domain; but revealing, as WikiLeaks did, that Hillary Clinton's secrets were empty secrets means taking away all power from him.
WikiLeaks has done no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but has done too much to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this injury to a very powerful power?
It is obvious that in the future, states will no longer be able to put on-line any reserved information - it would amount to publishing it on a poster glued to the corner of the street.
But it is equally clear that, with current technologies, it is in vain to hope that confidential telephone relations can be maintained.
Nothing easier than to find out if and when a head of state flew around and contacted one of his colleagues.
How can private and reserved relationships be maintained in the future?
I know that, for the moment, my forecast is science fiction and is therefore romantic, but I am obliged to imagine government agents who move discreetly in diligences with uncontrollable itineraries, carrying only messages learned by heart or, at most, hiding the rare information written in the heel of a shoe.
The information will be kept as a single copy in locked drawers: deep down, the attempt to espionage the Watergate has had less success than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that the technology is now advancing in crab, i.e. backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet restored a wire telegraph (telephones).
The videocassettes (analogs) had allowed film researchers to explore a film step by step, going forward and backwards and discovering all the secrets of editing, while now the CDs (digital) only allow to jump from chapter to chapter, i.e. by macroportions.
With the high-speed trains, we go from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, and the trips it includes, it takes three and a half hours.
It is therefore not extraordinary that the policy and communications techniques should go back to the horse cars.
One last observation.
In the past, the press was trying to understand what was going on in the secret of embassies.
Now it is the embassies that ask the press for confidential information.
Climate: how France is hacking its financing promises
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to review the implementation of the rapidly released financing promises (such as early start or early start financing) made by developed countries.
And the big French dowels are revealed.
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries pledged $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has pledged EUR 7.2 billion over three years and France EUR 1.26 billion (or EUR 420 million per year).
At the opening of COP16, the EU released the big game to persuade its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast start financing: report detailing the action of its member states, press conference, great side event, distribution of brochures...
The transparency exercise was valuable and appreciated: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same with the same level of precision.
The EU announced that it had released €2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on the right track to meet its commitment of $7.2 billion in 2012.
But when you look in detail, things are more complicated.
This money must, according to the Copenhagen agreement, be "new and additional" in order to ensure that an additional effort is made without being at the expense of official development assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no agreement on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission had proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
For example, the European Commission considered 2009 as a reference year: international financing is maintained, adding 150 million over three years to fast start financing.
Other countries have chosen similar references in terms of year or level of official development assistance.
On the other hand, France believes that funding for "all new projects" in 2010 is "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to expenditure in previous years or to the overall level of Official Development Assistance.
In concrete terms, France's total support to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease), it claims to respect its commitment to "new and additional" financing...
Another crucial element is the distribution between grants and loans.
Again, there is no rule and each chooses its method of calculation.
Some, like France, consider that 1€ loan is equivalent to 1€ given.
Obviously, this is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
While the use of loans can be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often emission mitigation projects that rely on more efficient technologies), it is misleading to present a euro that will be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is given... At the most, it should be counted under its commitments only the cost of the loan to the lending country (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate).
But France has nothing to do with such reasoning: it "respects" its commitment of €420 million by making 91.5% loans (€389.8 million) and 8.5% donations (€36.1 million) - see the EU document to verify for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union to use the loan so massively.
Germany requires 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (in other words) fulfil their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union put €1 in order to meet its commitment, France puts only 10 cents and considers that the effort is comparable.
Nice pass trick!
In short, in its fast start financing, France operates a double scam: on the one hand, on the evolution of the action over time and on the other hand, on the reality of the financial effort.
By spending only €36.1 million, it manages to make it believe that it spends 420 million "new and additional" in line with its promises.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that Bercy did the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other Member States continue to give if it is enough to lend?) and in the negotiations since the developing countries are not completely fooled...
The chapter on early financing is only a small, relatively short-term issue compared to all climate discussions.
But it could be one more grain of sand in the huge machine that is UNFCCC.
Let us hope that this will not be the case.
In any event, it is essential to learn from this first year of early financing.
First of all, France could announce a change in its method of accounting for the years 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and fairness with the other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France could move forward the discussions on the issues of long-term financing (another crucial chapter currently under discussion): the question of "additionality" or the method of accounting for loans will not escape.
France could change its position to become as progressive on these issues as it is on others.
Hope lies in the new Minister of the Environment, Ms Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about the fast start of France and its vision of "additionality" and the use of loans would increase the level of international confidence needed to move forward in the discussions.
